[2026-03-04T22:36:45Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QmLKrHRB4ETNwT4zLLq4Jm","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me compile a comprehensive analysis of the web handler implementation.\n\n## Web Handler Implementation Analysis\n\nI've thoroughly explored the web handler implementation in this project. Here's a complete breakdown of the four areas you requested:\n\n### 1. The Handler Struct and Options Pattern\n\n**Location:** `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` (lines 23-129)\n\nThe `Handler` struct is defined as:\n\n```go\ntype Handler struct {\n\tstore        ports.RunStore\n\tcaptures     ports.CaptureStore\n\tlogStore     ports.LogStore\n\tcontainer    ContainerLogger\n\tlogBroadcast *logstream.Broadcaster\n\tpages        map[string]*template.Template\n\tmux          *http.ServeMux\n}\n```\n\n**Required dependencies (set in NewHandler):**\n- `store` (ports.RunStore) - manages run data\n- `captures` (ports.CaptureStore) - manages step execution captures\n\n**Optional dependencies (set via HandlerOptions):**\n- `logStore` (ports.LogStore) - indexed log file lookup\n- `container` (ContainerLogger) - retrieves logs from containers\n- `logBroadcast` (*logstream.Broadcaster) - SSE streaming\n\n**Constructor:** `NewHandler(store ports.RunStore, captures ports.CaptureStore, opts ...HandlerOption)` (lines 73-129)\n\nThe constructor:\n1. Sets up template functions (`stateColor`, `healthColor`, `formatTime`, `formatDuration`, `truncate`, `shortContainerID`)\n2. Parses embedded templates (layout, projects, runs, run_detail)\n3. Creates the Handler with required dependencies\n4. Applies all options: `for _, opt := range opts { opt(h) }`\n5. Registers HTTP routes and static file serving\n6. Returns the fully configured handler\n\n### 2. The HandlerOption Functions Pattern\n\n**Location:** `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` (lines 23-44)\n\nThe options pattern uses a function type:\n\n```go\ntype HandlerOption func(*Handler)\n```\n\nThere are four option functions provided:\n\n1. **`WithContainerLogger(c ContainerLogger) HandlerOption`** (lines 26-29)\n   ```go\n   return func(h *Handler) { h.container = c }\n   ```\n\n2. **`WithContainerManager(c ContainerManager) HandlerOption`** (lines 31-34)\n   ```go\n   return func(h *Handler) { h.container = c }\n   ```\n   Note: `ContainerManager` extends `ContainerLogger` with lifecycle operations\n\n3. **`WithLogBroadcaster(b *logstream.Broadcaster) HandlerOption`** (lines 36-39)\n   ```go\n   return func(h *Handler) { h.logBroadcast = b }\n   ```\n\n4. **`WithLogStore(ls ports.LogStore) HandlerOption`** (lines 41-44)\n   ```go\n   return func(h *Handler) { h.logStore = ls }\n   ```\n\n**Key Interfaces for options:**\n\nFrom `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` (lines 51-60):\n\n```go\ntype ContainerLogger interface {\n\tLogs(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (string, error)\n}\n\ntype ContainerManager interface {\n\tContainerLogger\n\tRemove(ctx context.Context, containerID string) error\n\tInspect(ctx context.Context, containerID string) (*ports.ContainerStatus, error)\n}\n```\n\n**Usage in tests** (line 341):\n```go\nmgr := newMockContainerManager()\nh, err := NewHandler(store, store, WithContainerManager(mgr))\n```\n\n### 3. The handleAPITriggerOrchestrator Method\n\n**Location:** `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go` (lines 623-630)\n\n```go\nfunc (h *Handler) handleAPITriggerOrchestrator(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n\t// Placeholder endpoint — orchestrator integration is a separate feature.\n\t// Returns 202 Accepted to indicate the request was received.\n\tname := r.PathValue(\"name\")\n\tw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusAccepted)\n\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{\"status\": \"accepted\", \"project\": name})\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Handles `POST /api/projects/{name}/trigger` requests (registered at line 124)\n- Extracts project name from URL path using `r.PathValue(\"name\")`\n- Returns HTTP 202 Accepted status code (indicates request was received for async processing)\n- Returns JSON response: `{\"status\": \"accepted\", \"project\": \"<name>\"}`\n- Currently a **placeholder** — orchestrator integration is described as \"a separate feature\"\n\n**Test coverage** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler_test.go`, lines 537-551):\n\n```go\nfunc TestAPITriggerOrchestrator(t *testing.T) {\n\th, _ := setupHandler(t)\n\n\treq := httptest.NewRequest(\"POST\", \"/api/projects/myproject/trigger\", nil)\n\tw := httptest.NewRecorder()\n\th.ServeHTTP(w, req)\n\n\tassert.Equal(t, http.StatusAccepted, w.Code)\n\tassert.Contains(t, w.Header().Get(\"Content-Type\"), \"application/json\")\n\n\tvar result map[string]string\n\trequire.NoError(t, json.Unmarshal(w.Body.Bytes(), &result))\n\tassert.Equal(t, \"accepted\", result[\"status\"])\n\tassert.Equal(t, \"myproject\", result[\"project\"])\n}\n```\n\n### 4. The ListProjects Method on RunStore\n\n**Location:** `/workspace/internal/ports/store.go` (lines 10-18)\n\n```go\ntype RunStore interface {\n\tCreateRun(ctx context.Context, run *domain.Run) error\n\tGetRun(ctx context.Context, id string) (*domain.Run, error)\n\tUpdateRun(ctx context.Context, run *domain.Run) error\n\tDeleteRun(ctx context.Context, id string) error\n\tListRuns(ctx context.Context, since time.Time) ([]*domain.Run, error)\n\tListRunsByProject(ctx context.Context, projectDir string, since time.Time) ([]*domain.Run, error)\n\tListProjects(ctx context.Context) ([]string, error)\n}\n```\n\n**Method signature:**\n```go\nListProjects(ctx context.Context) ([]string, error)\n```\n\n**Returns:** A slice of project directory paths (as strings) or an error\n\n**Usage in handler** (lines 155, 231, 412, 425, 489):\n\n1. **In `handleProjectOverview`** (line 155):\n   ```go\n   projects, _ := h.store.ListProjects(r.Context())\n   labels := projectLabels(projects)\n   \n   for _, dir := range projects {\n       runs, err := h.store.ListRunsByProject(r.Context(), dir, time.Time{})\n       // ... calculate health, recent runs, active count\n   }\n   ```\n\n2. **In `handleAPIProjects`** (line 425):\n   ```go\n   projects, err := h.store.ListProjects(r.Context())\n   if err != nil {\n       http.Error(w, \"failed to list projects\", http.StatusInternalServerError)\n       return\n   }\n   labels := projectLabels(projects)\n   // ... build JSON response for each project\n   ```\n\n**Helper function - `projectLabels`** (lines 809-828):\n```go\nfunc projectLabels(dirs []string) map[string]string {\n\tlabels := make(map[string]string, len(dirs))\n\t// Group dirs by their base name to detect conflicts.\n\tbyBase := map[string][]string{}\n\tfor _, d := range dirs {\n\t\tbase := filepath.Base(d)\n\t\tbyBase[base] = append(byBase[base], d)\n\t}\n\tfor base, paths := range byBase {\n\t\tif len(paths) == 1 {\n\t\t\tlabels[paths[0]] = base\n\t\t} else {\n\t\t\tfor _, p := range paths {\n\t\t\t\tparent := filepath.Base(filepath.Dir(p))\n\t\t\t\tlabels[p] = parent + \"/\" + base\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn labels\n}\n```\n\nThis function converts full directory paths to display-friendly labels, handling naming conflicts by adding parent directory names when needed (e.g., `/home/foo/bar` → `\"foo/bar\"` when there's a conflict).\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe web handler uses a sophisticated options pattern where `HandlerOption` functions allow optional configuration of container management, log streaming, and log storage features. The `handleAPITriggerOrchestrator` is currently a placeholder returning 202 Accepted. The `ListProjects` method is central to the dashboard, returning all project directories from the store, which are then converted to human-readable labels and used to display project health, recent runs, and container management information."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aafc87